 \frac {
   \Gamma , x:A  \mid   \phi { \left ( x \right )}  :  \mathsf { prop } 
   \qquad  
   \Gamma   \vdash   \exists  x : A.  \top 
}{
   \Gamma \mid   { \left ( \epsilon  x:A.  \phi { \left ( x \right )} \right )}  : A
   \qquad  
   \Gamma ,z:A  \mid   \phi { \left ( z \right )}   \vdash   \phi { \left ( \epsilon  x:A. \phi { \left ( x \right )} \right )} 
}

mainmatter.p:
One of the most common tasks when working in univalent foundations is to characterize the path space of a given type, i.e. establish a structure identity principle. Formalized SIP proofs often follow a baroque style involving identity systems and the even more complex displayed identity systems, etc. that sometimes obscure the very simple informal reasoning behind a given structure identity principle; 

    the proposal is to develop a formal proof language to better reflect this informal reasoning, backed by a suite of lemmas and tactics

.
